am sure my experiences are similar to others, but from a caster perspective.<br>
<br>
The days and hours before you scrounge up every scrap of resist gear possible, knowing 1 point could mean the difference between life and icecube.  Ya then start the trek to Permafrost, giving you time to think - I am going to die, I wont get any loot..why am I going?  The you get together with all the other raiders, ask last minute advice, discuss tactics with other people of your class etc.  People fool around, make jokes - prolly to release tension.<br>
<br>
The raid leader comes along (Kerna), and forms the groups, its all a bit chaotic, then the order to enter the zone comes.  Ya wander in, all groups enter, then we all follow the golden blue Dorf to the King room.  People mill around, casters beg for crack, buffs fly left right and centre.  Noone really knows where to sit, what to do, then the puller calls out Inc Frost Giants. <br>
<br>
This is when everything comes together, everyone knows how to kill stuff and funtion in a team, spells fly, tanks attack, chanters call whats mezzed, the puller calls to reassist, and then the big blue smurfs all die.  I can say that it was a pleasure to be on a raid with 33 very cool, calm, and professional players, the depth of raiding experience blew me away (Orinworf, Crombattleaxe, Siilverain come to mind)<br>
<br>
We all get to the buff hall, and as far as I know it all went smoothly, I dont know why Levitate wasnt part of it, considering all the pit traps and the Lady's dragonfear.  I expect it stems from A Necro trying to be useful!<br>
<br>
We logged and Kerna told us our tactics, mine were easy, send in my, pet, wait until 50, then run up and Nuke.<br>
We ran in, I used my hot keys to pump mana in Hinmera and Shimi (Clerics both), then when the command came I charged.<br>
<br>
I don't know how many times I resisted fear, and it seemed every step I took I lost a bubble of life.  Also the lag made the short run seem to last for minutes rather than a few seconds.  When I saw my health dropping so quickly it was hard to resist 49 levels of trained running instinct and to keep going forward!<br>
<br>
I got to Vox, I think I managed to cast 2 life taps, her health bar hadn't caught up, according to what I saw she was still at 90% life.  I thought something had gone wrong, and we had to go and die to save the tanks.<br>
<br>
Then she dropped! I remebered to take screen shots, people got ressed and healed, the loot devided.  Without any disrespect intended to Kerna, no one really know the after fight procedure.  People bailed very quickly, unfortunaltely the clerics were among them.  In hindsigt I also shoulve bought some coffins with me to recover those that had fallen down the pits.  Luckily my fellow Necro Sakkath ported to OT and came back with one from his bank.<br>
<br>
Once I got a port out (thanks Jex) it was an odd feeling hanging around in WC.  I kindof expected people to know that we had all just killed a Dragon! but it was the same old /ooc and /auction stuff.  The mobs in WC seemed tiny, the'd be specks on Giants and Vox's feet.  Then the adrenaline and the rush wore off, and life returned to normal.<br>
<br>
See you all next time! and a huge thankyou to each and every one of you who made that raid my most enjoyable and memorable EQ moment to date.  (Even Crom who called me a bearded Gnome)<br>
 <p>Melifleur<Br>49 Necromancer<Br>Heart of Fenris</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/utaneidien.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Taneidien</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 40<br> <font color=#E9D756>(9/8/01 4:23:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=591.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Memoirs of a Dragon Slayer</span><hr size=1> Im glad you had a memorable first dragon hunt.  They are a blast, especially when they go off as planned.  I hope you have many more equally enjoyable dragon hunts<br>
